only","Epidural space only","Subarachnoid space only","Subarachnoid space and brain parenchyma","Subdural space only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid space and brain parenchyma\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as meningoencephalitis involves inflammation of both the meninges (specifically in the subarachnoid space) and brain tissue (parenchyma). This is evidenced by MRI findings showing both leptomeningeal enhancement and parenchymal inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidural space\u003C/strong\u003E is not usually involved in meningoencephalitis. This potential space lies between the dura mater and the skull, and infection here would constitute an epidural abscess with different clinical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural space\u003C/strong\u003E is another potential space between the dura and arachnoid mater. While subdural empyema can occur as a complication of meningitis, it is not the primary site of infection in meningoencephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid space only\u003C/strong\u003E would describe meningitis without parenchymal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain parenchyma only\u003C/strong\u003E would describe isolated encephalitis. The presence of neck stiffness, meningeal signs, and CSF findings indicate meningeal involvement in addition to parenchymal inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meningoencephalitis involves infection of both the meninges (subarachnoid space) and brain parenchyma.","The distinction between meningitis and encephalitis is important as it affects both diagnostic approach and treatment choices.","Combined meningoencephalitis often indicates a more severe infection with worse prognosis than isolated meningitis or encephalitis."],"references":["Greenberg SB. Viral Meningitis and Encephalitis. Office Practice of Neurology. 2003:466\u20139. doi: 10.1016/B0-44-306557-8/50066-6. Epub 2009 May 18. PMCID: PMC7173605.","Steiner I, Budka H, Chaudhuri A, Koskiniemi M, Sainio K, Salonen O, Kennedy PG. Viral meningoencephalitis: a review of diagnostic methods and guidelines for management. Eur J Neurol. 2010 Aug;17(8):999-e57. doi: 10.1111/j.1468-1331.2010.02970.x. Epub 2010 Mar 3. PMID: 20236175.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T16:53:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:04:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9160"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74990"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/